const description = "New to Vampire Crawlers? This beginner's guide covers card types, combat basics, deckbuilding tips, dungeon progression, and how to survive your first runs.";
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} canonical="https://vampcrawlers.cc/guides/beginners-guide">
  <article>
    <div class="breadcrumbs">
      <a href="/">Home</a><span>/</span>Beginner's Guide
    </div>

    <h1>Beginner's Guide</h1>
    <p class="lead">Everything new players need to know about poncle's turn-based deckbuilder. No spoilers for dungeons beyond Mad Forest.</p>

    <div class="toc">
      <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
      <ol>
        <li><a href="#what-is">What Is Vampire Crawlers?</a></li>
        <li><a href="#cards">Understanding Cards &amp; Colors</a></li>
        <li><a href="#combat">Combat Basics</a></li>
        <li><a href="#village">The Village Hub</a></li>
        <li><a href="#deckbuilding">Deckbuilding 101</a></li>
        <li><a href="#early">Early Game Walkthrough</a></li>
        <li><a href="#tips">Quick Tips &amp; Tricks</a></li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <h2 id="what-is">What Is Vampire Crawlers?</h2>
    <p>Vampire Crawlers is a <strong>turn-based deckbuilder with roguelite elements</strong> from poncle, the creators of Vampire Survivors. Released April 21, 2026 on Steam, Xbox Series S|X, PlayStation 5, and Nintendo Switch.</p>
    <div class="info-box">
      <strong>Key Difference:</strong> Vampire Survivors is real-time auto-attack (bullet heaven). Vampire Crawlers is <strong>turn-based</strong> — you play cards one at a time. Strategy &gt; reflexes. If you die in Vampire Crawlers, it's because you built a bad deck, not because you dodged poorly.
    </div>

    <h2 id="cards">Understanding Cards &amp; Colors</h2>
    <p>Every card belongs to one of six color-coded types. Recognizing them is the foundation of deckbuilding:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong class="c-red">Attack (Red)</strong> — Deal damage. Your primary tool for clearing encounters. 37 cards, from 0-cost Whip to 5-cost Vandalier (500 damage).</li>
      <li><strong class="c-blue">Defense (Blue)</strong> — Generate Armor that absorbs damage before it hits your HP. 7 cards. <em>Pummarola</em> and <em>Pummadora</em> also provide post-encounter healing.</li>
      <li><strong class="c-yellow">Stat Boost (Yellow)</strong> — Temporary stat increases. Some are <strong>Destroy-type</strong> (one use per battle, like <em>Crown</em> for XP growth). 18 cards.</li>
      <li><strong class="c-purple">Mana (Purple)</strong> — Generate the mana you need to play other cards. 6 cards. <em>Empty Tome</em> (0 cost, +1 mana) is excellent.</li>
      <li><strong class="c-teal">Character (Teal)</strong> — 22 unique cards tied to characters. Each has a play effect and an ongoing trigger.</li>
      <li><strong style="color:#ccc">Wild (White)</strong> — Cost <code>W</code> (any mana color). <em>Wings</em> reduces next card cost by 1. <em>Bracelet</em> deals 100 damage.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <strong>Color synergy matters.</strong> Characters trigger effects based on specific colors you play. Antonio grants +10% damage when you play a <strong class="c-red">red</strong> card. Build around your leading character's trigger color.
    </div>

    <h2 id="combat">Combat Basics</h2>
    <p>Each dungeon floor has enemy encounters — beat all enemies to advance. Key mechanics:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Mana</strong> — Resource for playing cards. Generated by purple Mana cards. Unspent mana is lost at turn end.</li>
      <li><strong>Armor</strong> — Blue shield that absorbs damage. Applied before HP damage. Stack it early in tough fights.</li>
      <li><strong>Hand Size</strong> — Cards you can hold at once. <em>Bracer</em> and <em>Poppea</em> increase it. The bigger your hand, the more options per turn.</li>
      <li><strong>Combo Multiplier</strong> — Playing cards in ascending mana cost order builds a combo. Higher combo = more damage. The <em>Combo Stack</em> relic is essential for this.</li>
      <li><strong>Evolutions</strong> — Certain cards evolve when paired with specific relics or conditions. Check the Grim Grimoire (from Library West Wing) to see discovered combos.</li>
      <li><strong>Disarm</strong> — <em>Garlic</em> and <em>Soul Eater</em> can disarm enemies, preventing their next attack.</li>
      <li><strong>Freeze</strong> — <em>Clock Lancet</em> freezes enemies for one turn.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="formula-box">
      Combo Damage = Base Damage × (1 + Combo Stack Bonus × Combo Count)
    </div>

    <h2 id="village">The Village Hub</h2>
    <p>Between dungeon runs, you return to the Village. As you collect relics, more locations unlock:</p>
    <div class="grid-2">
      <div class="card">
        <h3 style="font-size:0.92rem;font-weight:700;color:var(--text-primary);margin:0 0 0.35rem">Gorton Bell Inn</h3>
        <p style="font-size:0.85rem;color:var(--text-secondary);margin:0">Buy and equip characters (up to 5). Your <strong>leading character</strong> adds their stats + 4 cards to your deck. Additional characters add 1 card each.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3 style="font-size:0.92rem;font-weight:700;color:var(--text-primary);margin:0 0 0.35rem">Blacksmith</h3>
        <p style="font-size:0.85rem;color:var(--text-secondary);margin:0">Socket gems into cards for permanent stat bonuses. Unlocked by the <strong>Stardust Anvil</strong> relic. Customize gem drops with <strong>Lapidary Loupe</strong>.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3 style="font-size:0.92rem;font-weight:700;color:var(--text-primary);margin:0 0 0.35rem">Fortune Teller</h3>
        <p style="font-size:0.85rem;color:var(--text-secondary);margin:0">Arcana system — powerful run-wide passive bonuses. Unlocked by the <strong>Polentir</strong> relic from Furious Forest.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3 style="font-size:0.92rem;font-weight:700;color:var(--text-primary);margin:0 0 0.35rem">Museum</h3>
        <p style="font-size:0.85rem;color:var(--text-secondary);margin:0">View and toggle collected relics. Available from the start. Relics can be turned off if you want a harder challenge.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2 id="deckbuilding">Deckbuilding 101</h2>
    <p><strong>The golden rule:</strong> a lean, focused deck beats a bloated one every time.</p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Mana curve.</strong> Have enough 0-1 cost cards to start combos. Don't fill your deck with 4-5 cost finishers you can't afford to play.</li>
      <li><strong>Synergy over power.</strong> A 0-cost Whip (8 damage, multi-target) that triggers your character's effect is better than a 5-cost card you can't combo into.</li>
      <li><strong>Trim when you can.</strong> Some events let you remove cards. Remove cards that don't synergize with your build.</li>
      <li><strong>Start small, scale up.</strong> Early encounters should be used to set up your engine (mana, hand size, stat boosts), then unleash big damage in later turns.</li>
      <li><strong>One defense card is enough.</strong> Don't load up on Blue cards. One good Armor generator + healing is usually sufficient.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2 id="early">Early Game Walkthrough</h2>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Clear Mad Forest.</strong> It's the only starting dungeon. Explores basic mechanics. Find the <em>Gem Hammer</em> relic (break crates/barrels).</li>
      <li><strong>Reach Level 10 in Mad Forest.</strong> Even if you die immediately after, you unlock <strong>Inlaid Library</strong>. Level unlocks are permanent.</li>
      <li><strong>Collect Combo Stack.</strong> The tutorial gives it automatically. This relic is <em>the</em> core scaling mechanic. Never unequip it.</li>
      <li><strong>Buy characters at the Inn.</strong> More characters = more starter deck cards = more options in early encounters.</li>
      <li><strong>Run Inlaid Library.</strong> Reach Level 15 here to unlock <strong>Teeny Bridge</strong> (which gives Stardust Anvil + Overkill — two essential relics).</li>
      <li><strong>Branch out.</strong> Once you have Combo Stack, Gem Hammer, Stardust Anvil, and Overkill, you can tackle any dungeon chain.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2 id="tips">Quick Tips &amp; Tricks</h2>
    <div class="tip-box"><strong>Level thresholds unlock dungeons.</strong> You don't need to win — just hit Level 10 or 15. Die immediately after, the unlock still counts.</div>
    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Don't skip relics.</strong> Relics are permanent and can be toggled but are always available. Hidden in breakable objects (barrels, crates, torches). The <em>Guiding Light</em> relic shows destructibles on the minimap.</div>
    <div class="info-box"><strong>Disco Mode.</strong> After buying 5+ characters at the Inn, there's a 10% chance per room that Disco Mode triggers — granting a 5% discount on all purchases for that visit.</div>
    <ul>
      <li>Gems (unlocked by <em>Gem Hammer</em>) add permanent bonuses to individual cards at the Blacksmith</li>
      <li>Arcanas (unlocked by <em>Polentir</em>) provide run-wide passive bonuses — selected before each run</li>
      <li>The <em>Overkill</em> relic lets you keep attacking bosses after defeat for bonus gold (cap increases with upgrades)</li>
      <li>Break <em>everything</em> — relics, gold, and gems are often hidden in destructible objects</li>
    </ul>

